  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-ijc.22820.pdf_4_76",
    "text": "The apoptotic effect of flavopiridol was mainly mediated by mitochondrial pathway in the ADR clones of OS and EFTs",
    "canon_role": "section_header",
    "bbox": [
      0.507692317533202,
      0.5973837209090307,
      0.8596153841078236,
      0.6206395347208142
    ],
    "page": "docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-ijc.22820.pdf_4",
    "order": 78
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-ijc.22820.pdf_4_77",
    "text": "We next investigated whether the activation of caspase-9 and caspase-3 were attributed to the mitochondrial injury, which could lead to release of cytochrome c. Treatments of parental and ADR clones of OS and EFTs with 400 and 320 nM flavopiridol resulted in the expression of cytochrome c in the cytosolic fractions of the treated cells (Fig. 4a). It is reported that disruption of the balance between propoptotic and antiapoptotic proteins, e.g. altered Bax/ Bel-2 ratio, is a precursor for the release of cytochrome c from miand that Bax gene is a target of p53 and can be reguisab. 53 via transeniptional dependent?. or independent mechIn the present study, as shown in Figure 4b, the treatments of MNNG/ADR and WE-68/ADR cells with flavopiridol resulted in a decrease in the Bcl-2 and Bcl-xL expression in a dose-dependent manner. On the other hand, flavopiridol dosedependently increased Bax and p53 expression in WE-68/ADR cells, but not in MNNG/ADR cells. This difference in response may relate to the difference in p53 status, which is wild-type in WE-68 and mutant in MNNG.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5055024437479128,
      0.6249999999219907,
      0.903846157333927,
      0.832914153984014
    ],
    "page": "docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-ijc.22820.pdf_4",
    "order": 79
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-ijc.22820.pdf_4_50",
    "text": "time-dependent manner in ADR clones of OS and EFTs, as indicated by the reduction in the intensites of proenzymes of caspase9 and caspase-3, and increase in the cleaved products of caspase-8 (Fig. 3a). Co-treatment with a broad-spectrum caspase inhibitor (Z-VAD-FMK) or a caspase-3 specific inhibitor (Z-DEVD-FMK) significantly reduced the efficacy of flavopiridol on the induction of the cell death in ADR cells, but a caspase-s specific inhibitor (Z-IETD-FMK) could not inhibit the cell death (Fig. 3b). As shown in Figure 3c, 75 uM Z-VAD-FMK and 50 uM Z-DEVD-",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
